, is democratic accountability, not court review.[3] For the history here y=
ou can read Justice Gorsuch=E2=80=99s Gundy dissent, or honestly=C2=A0Wikip=
edia. For the statutory authority for various SEC rules, you can read the p=
roposing releases. For instance, the climate disclosure proposal, citing va=
rious sections of the Securities Act of 1933 and the Securities Exchange Ac=
t of 1934,=C2=A0says: =E2=80=9CThe Commission has broad authority to promul=
gate disclosure requirements that are =E2=80=98necessary or appropriate in =
the public interest or for the protection of investors.=E2=80=99=C2=A0We ha=
ve considered this statutory standard and determined that disclosure of inf=
ormation about climate-related risks and metrics would be in the public int=
erest and would protect investors. In making this determination, we have al=
so considered whether the proposed disclosures =E2=80=98will promote effici=
ency, competition, and capital formation.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D The stock buyba=
ck proposal is less explicit, but also cites various statutory sections tha=
t generally give the SEC authority to make rules =E2=80=9Cas necessary or a=
ppropriate in the public interest or for the protection of investors.=E2=80=
=9D[4] Four justices voted to uphold the rule, in an opinion written by Jus=
tice Elena Kagan. Three voted against, in an opinion written by Justice Nei=
l Gorsuch. Justice Samuel=C2=A0Alito voted to uphold the rule, and wrote a =
concurrence saying in essence that he would rather have voted against, but =
didn=E2=80=99t have the votes: =E2=80=9CSince 1935, the Court has uniformly=
 rejected nondelegation arguments and has upheld provisions that authorized=
 agencies to adopt important rules pursuant to extraordinarily capacious st=
andards. =E2=80=A6 If a majority of this Court were willing to reconsider t=
he approach we have taken for the past 84 years, I would support that effor=
t. But because a majority is not willing to do that, it would be freakish t=
o single out the provision at issue here for special treatment.=E2=80=9D Ju=
stice Brett Kavanaugh was confirmed to the court a few days after the oral =
argument in Gundy, and did not vote. Incidentally, during oral argument in =
Gundy, Justice Stephen Breyer =E2=80=94 who was=C2=A0an expert on administr=
ative law before becoming a judge =E2=80=94=C2=A0asked whether reviving the=
 nondelegation doctrine would undermine the SEC. After all, the guiding pri=
nciple for the authority delegated to the SEC is quite broad, and the SEC m=
akes a lot of rules. Are they all unconstitutional?[5] The three in Gundy (=
Gorsuch, John Roberts and Clarence Thomas), plus Alito (who essentially agr=
eed with Gorsuch in Gundy), Kavanaugh (who joined the court a week after Gu=
ndy) and Amy Coney Barrett (who joined later).[6]=C2=A0This is actually a p=
retty common move,=C2=A0striking down administrative decisions because of s=
ome constitutional objection to the rules for how personnel are appointed.=
=C2=A0SEC ALJ appointments were declared unconstitutional once before, and =
modified to fix the problem, but now I guess they are unconstitutional agai=
n and need to be fixed some more. Except that trials by SEC ALJs are appare=
ntly unconstitutional anyway, so fixing the appointment process=C2=A0won=E2=
=80=99t really help.[7] Citations omitted.[8] Also, to be clear, the bankin=
g regulators, and the Environmental Protection Agency, and every other admi=
nistrative agency. This is a finance column, and this case is about the SEC=
, so I am talking about the SEC. But the implications are much broader.[9] =
Bankers generally make most of their money for actually closing a deal, tho=
ugh given the situation here =E2=80=94=C2=A0Twitter hired advisers to consi=
der Musk=E2=80=99s semi-hostile offer and possibly fend him off =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0I assume its bankers will get something even if he goes away. Still l=
ess than they=E2=80=99d get for a closed deal. Lawyers tend to be paid more=
 for work (by the hour, etc.) than for success, but in high-profile M&A som=
e success-based pay is not uncommon.[10] Not=C2=A0a real thing, I don=E2=80=
=99t think.
