</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Article I, Section 1 of the <a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27769856.275619/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuYXJjaGl2ZXMuZ292L2ZvdW5kaW5nLWRvY3MvY29uc3RpdHV0aW9uLXRyYW5zY3JpcHQ/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4c9a7261" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">US Constitution</a> says: =E2=80=9C=
All legislative Powers herein granted shall be vested in a Congress of the =
United States, which shall consist of a Senate and House of Representatives=
.=E2=80=9D One way to paraphrase that is: Federal law is made by Congress.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the modern US, this is not quite true.=
=C2=A0<em>Some=C2=A0</em>federal law is made by Congress, but quite a lot o=
f federal law is made by government departments and administrative agencies=
. In many cases, Congress passes fairly general laws, and those laws instru=
ct the relevant agency to write rules implementing the laws, and then the a=
gencies write more specific rules. Sometimes these rules just fill in detai=
ls in a comprehensive statutory scheme. Other times the agencies have prett=
y broad mandates to write rules that are in the public interest, and they g=
et to set their own agendas and decide what that means.</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">There is quite a large body of law and procedure governing how=
 those agencies write those rules, and those rules are pretty important. Ar=
ound here, we have talked recently about a bunch of proposed rules from the=
 US Securities and Exchange Commission that would, for instance, crack down=
 on <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27769856.27561=
9/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMzEvd=
GhlLXNlYy1pcy1jb21pbmctZm9yLXNwYWNzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MTkyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0=
bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDUxOSZ1dG1=
fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdfe9b525" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> spe=
cial purpose acquisition companies</a>, require more <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27769856.275619/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21i=
ZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMjQvdGhlLXNlYy13YW50cy10by1zdG9=
wLWFjdGl2aXNtP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MTkyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdX=
RtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDUxOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzd=
HVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2523186f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> disclosure of activist =
stakes and swap positions</a>, limit <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/27769856.275619/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlu=
aW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTItMTYvdGhlLXNlYy1oYXMtYmlnLXBsYW5zP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA=
1MTkyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJn=
V0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDUxOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cBd81c59bf" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;"> stock buybacks and executives trading in their own st=
ocks</a>, and most notably <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/27769856.275619/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydG=
ljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMjIvdGhlLXNlYy13aWxsLXJlZ3VsYXRlLWNsaW1hdGU_Y21waWQ9QkJEM=
DUxOTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXIm=
dXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNTE5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB5b9407cf" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;"> implement a climate disclosure regime</a>. This is mo=
stly stuff that the SEC is doing on its own initiative under laws passed mo=
stly in the 1930s and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/27769856.275619/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvV2lsbGlhbXNfQWN=
0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3b994741" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">1960s</a>. Congress largely=C2=
=A0set up the SEC and its underlying system of securities laws in the 1930s=
, and the SEC took it from there.[1]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There =
are obviously good reasons to do things this way. Congress does not have ti=
me to write all the rules, so delegating rulemaking to agencies is efficien=
t. Congress also has limited subject-matter expertise: The SEC knows more a=
bout securities law and financial markets than the average congressperson, =
so it makes sense for the SEC to write most of the securities rules. The ru=
lemaking process is often both more flexible=C2=A0and more=C2=A0<em>thought=
ful=C2=A0</em>than the legislative process; agencies have to consider publi=
c comments and explain their reasoning in a way that Congress does not. Age=
ncy rules can be overturned by a court if they are =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27769856.275619/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cub=
GF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L3VzY29kZS90ZXh0LzUvNzA2/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB61b1ff=
49" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">arbitrary and capricious</a>,=E2=80=9D which is not generally =
true of laws passed by Congress; Congress can be as arbitrary as it wants.[=
2]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are also objections though. Congre=
ss is elected, and the SEC isn=E2=80=99t. Letting agencies write rules is m=
ore technocratic but less democratic; the agencies might be more captured b=
y industry or just by longtime staffers who are less politically accountabl=
e. Also, let=E2=80=99s be clear, in the modern US, a lot of people simply t=
hink that there should be=C2=A0<em>fewer=C2=A0</em>rules overall. If you th=
ink that then you will object to the whole idea of agencies writing rules: =
If only Congress could make law, then there would be fewer rules about, say=
, securities fraud. (Or environmental regulation or workplace safety or ban=
k capital or whatever else you are interested in.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">Also the constitution does say =E2=80=9C<em>all=C2=A0</em>legislati=
ve powers=E2=80=9D are vested in Congress. If you take that literally,=C2=
=A0you might think that it=E2=80=99s unconstitutional for the SEC to make a=
ny rules at all.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The rise of the US a=
dministrative state =E2=80=94=C2=A0all these agencies making all these rule=
s =E2=80=94 is most identified with the New Deal in the 1930s. At the time,=
 people objected that it was in fact unconstitutional for agencies to make =
rules. The US Supreme Court occasionally agreed: In two 1935 cases, the Sup=
reme Court struck down laws that delegated rulemaking authority to executiv=
e agencies. Then that stopped, and the administrative state grew. Since 193=
5, lots of people have challenged agency rulemaking under the =E2=80=9Cnond=
elegation doctrine,=E2=80=9D the theory that Congress cannot delegate legis=
lative authority to agencies, but they have never won. The Supreme Court ha=
s adopted an =E2=80=9Cintelligible principle=E2=80=9D test, saying that if =
Congress delegates authority to an agency and gives it an =E2=80=9Cintellig=
ible principle=E2=80=9D to follow, then the agency can constitutionally mak=
e rules guided by that principle. This is a vague test and in practice, for=
 the last 87 years, it has always been met. For instance, Congress has give=
n the SEC pretty broad authority to make disclosure rules that are =E2=80=
=9Cnecessary or appropriate in the public interest for the protection of in=
vestors,=E2=80=9D which gives the SEC a lot of discretion but which=C2=A0is=
 probably =E2=80=9Cintelligible=E2=80=9D enough under current law.[3]</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is changing now, though. I am enough of a l=
egal realist to say that it is changing because there have been a bunch of =
Republican judicial appointments, including to the Supreme Court, in recent=
 years, and elite Republican lawyers are skeptical of=C2=A0the modern admin=
istrative state and want to revive the nondelegation doctrine.=C2=A0</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is where I need to make a personal disclosur=
e-brag. My wife is a federal=C2=A0criminal defense lawyer, and a few years =
ago she argued a case in the Supreme Court. The case =E2=80=94=C2=A0<a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27769856.275619/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuc3VwcmVtZWNvdXJ0Lmdvdi9vcGluaW9ucy8xOHBkZi8xNy02MDg2XzJiOGUucGRm/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4ab79e35" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Gundy v. United States</a> =E2=80=
=94 concerned a fairly technical Justice Department rule about=C2=A0sex off=
ender registries. But the argument was about the nondelegation doctrine: It=
 was about whether it was constitutional for the Justice Department to make=
 rules like that under delegated authority from Congress. It was the sort o=
f case that would not have made it to the Supreme Court a decade earlier =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0<em>obviously=C2=A0</em>this is constitutional, everyone wou=
ld have said =E2=80=94=C2=A0but times were changing. The nondelegation doct=
rine might be coming back.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Arguing in the S=
upreme Court is kind of a big deal, and I came to the argument to watch. Si=
tting in the audience before the argument, I ran into Jay Clayton, who was =
then the chair of the SEC. We said hello, and I asked if he was there becau=
se of the implications of the case for his agency. He looked puzzled: No, t=
his was a sex-offender case; he was there because his friend was arguing th=
e case for the government.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">After the argume=
nt he said to me something to the effect of=C2=A0=E2=80=9CI see what you me=
an.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My wife lost. Barely. The Supr=
eme Court ruled, in a strange 5-3 vote,[4] that the delegation at issue the=
re was constitutional. Justice Neil Gorsuch wrote a dissent in Gundy, and i=
t=E2=80=99s stuff like this:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Wh=
y did the framers insist on this particular arrangement? They believed the =
new federal government=E2=80=99s most dangerous power was the power to enac=
t laws restricting the people=E2=80=99s liberty.=C2=A0An =E2=80=9Cexcess of=
 law-making=E2=80=9D was, in their words, one of =E2=80=9Cthe diseases to w=
hich our governments are most liable.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0To address that tendenc=
y, the framers went to great lengths to make lawmaking difficult. In Articl=
e I, by far the longest part of the Constitution, the=C2=A0framers insisted=
 that any proposed law must win the approval of two Houses of Congress=E2=
=80=94elected at different times, by different constituencies, and for diff=
erent terms in office=E2=80=94and either secure the President=E2=80=99s app=
roval or obtain enough support to override his veto. Some occasionally comp=
lain about Article I=E2=80=99s detailed and arduous processes for new legis=
lation, but to the framers these were bulwarks of liberty. =E2=80=A6</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Restricting the task of legislating to one branch=
 characterized by difficult and deliberative processes was also designed to=
 promote fair notice and the rule of law, ensuring the people would be subj=
ect to a relatively stable and predictable set of rules. And by directing t=
hat legislating be done only by elected representatives in a public process=
, the Constitution sought to ensure that the lines of accountability would =
be clear: The sovereign people would know, without ambiguity, whom to hold =
accountable for the laws they would have to follow.</p></blockquote><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In Gorsuch=E2=80=99s view, if =E2=80=9CCongress makes=
 the policy decisions,=E2=80=9D it is okay for executive agencies to =E2=80=
=9Cfill up the details.=E2=80=9D And =E2=80=9Conce Congress prescribes the =
rule governing private conduct, it may make the application of that rule de=
pend on executive fact-finding.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0But policy decisions have to =
be made by Congress, not by agencies. He added:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">Nor would enforcing the Constitution=E2=80=99s demands spe=
ll doom for what some call the =E2=80=9Cadministrative state.=E2=80=9D The =
separation of powers does not prohibit any particular policy outcome, let a=
lone dictate any conclusion about the proper size and scope of government. =
Instead, it is a procedural guarantee that requires Congress to assemble a =
social consensus before choosing our nation=E2=80=99s course on policy ques=
tions like those implicated by SORNA. What is more, Congress is hardly bere=
ft of options to accomplish all it might wish to achieve. It may always aut=
horize executive branch officials to fill in even a large number of details=
, to find facts that trigger the generally applicable rule of conduct speci=
fied in a statute, or to exercise non-legislative powers. Congress can also=
 commission agencies or other experts to study and recommend legislative la=
nguage. Respecting the separation of powers forecloses no substantive outco=
mes. It only requires us to respect along the way one of the most vital of =
the procedural protections of individual liberty found in our Constitution.=
=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That was several years =
ago, though, and since then the personnel of the court has changed some mor=
e. It is plausible that there are now as many as six votes for Gorsuch=E2=
=80=99s position.[5]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yesterday the U.S. Cou=
rt of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit, in Texas, ruled that the SEC is uncons=
titutional? Not really. But here is an opinion in <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27769856.275619/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2E1LnVzY29=
1cnRzLmdvdi9vcGluaW9ucy9wdWIvMjAvMjAtNjEwMDctQ1YwLnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB50f7e2c9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">Jarkesy v. SEC</a>, where the SEC brought an admini=
strative action against a hedge fund manager named George Jarkesy, accusing=
 him=C2=A0of fraud. Instead of suing Jarkesy in federal court, the SEC, as =
it sometimes does, brought an administrative action against him in its own =
internal hearing system; instead of a judge and jury, the case=C2=A0was hea=
rd by an SEC official called an =E2=80=9Cadministrative law judge.=E2=80=9D=
 The ALJ found against Jarkesy, fined him almost a million dollars and bann=
ed him from the industry; Jarkesy appealed to the commissioners of the SEC,=
 who upheld the ALJ=E2=80=99s judgment. Then he appealed to the Fifth Circu=
it, arguing that all of this was unconstitutional.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">The Fifth Circuit panel, by a 2-1 vote,=C2=A0agreed, for three reas=
ons. One reason is that, by suing him in its own tribunal, the SEC deprived=
 him of the right to a jury trial: The SEC fined him a million dollars for =
fraud, without having to prove its case to a jury. The Fifth Circuit found =
this unconstitutional under the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/27769856.275619/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYXJjaGl2ZXMuZ292L2ZvdW5kaW5nL=
WRvY3MvYmlsbC1vZi1yaWdodHMtdHJhbnNjcmlwdA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2615f2c0=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-colo=
r: #ccc;">Seventh Amendment</a>, which guarantees a right to a jury in civi=
l cases. I think I agree? At Bloomberg Opinion back in 2015, <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27769856.275619/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTUtMTAtMDIvc2VjLXMtbmV3LWNvdXJ=
0LXBvd2Vycy1hcmVuLXQtZ29pbmctYXdheT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTE5MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG=
1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA1MTkmdXRtX=
2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4e445e09" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Noah=
 Feldman wrote</a>=C2=A0a good column about this case, saying that it was =
=E2=80=9Cworth noting, and mourning, this impending incremental erosion of =
the constitutional protections of a civil trial and the jury right that goe=
s hand in hand with it.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0The SEC has always had the power to b=
ring fraud cases in federal court, and has a pretty=C2=A0good record there.=
 But in 2010, Congress gave the SEC the power to pursue monetary penalties =
in its own courts if it wanted to. This always seems to <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27769856.275619/aHR0cHM6Ly90YXgudGhvb=
XNvbnJldXRlcnMuY29tL25ld3MvY3JpdGljcy1wcmVzcy1mb3ItcmVmb3JtLWFzLXNlYy1mYWls=
cy10by1zZXBhcmF0ZS1lbmZvcmNlbWVudC1hbmQtYWRqdWRpY2F0b3J5LWZ1bmN0aW9ucy8/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdc352791" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">cause</a> more <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27769856.275619/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuam9uZX=
NkYXkuY29tL2VuL2luc2lnaHRzLzIwMTgvMDYvdXMtc3VwcmVtZS1jb3VydC1ob2xkcy1zZWNzL=
XN0YWZmLWFwcG9pbnRtZW50cy1mb3I/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7f7311af" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
trouble</a> than it saves, and is apparently unconstitutional, and I am not=
 sure the SEC will miss it all that much.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A=
nother reason is that the process for appointing and removing SEC ALJs is u=
nconstitutional, for reasons=C2=A0that honestly I find unbearably boring an=
d so will not talk about.[6]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the third =
reason is the nondelegation doctrine: The Fifth Circuit found that Congress=
 unconstitutionally delegated to the SEC the power to decide whether to bri=
ng cases in federal court or before its own ALJs[7]:</p><blockquote><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Congress has delegated to the SEC what would be legis=
lative power absent a guiding intelligible principle. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Throug=
h Dodd=E2=80=93Frank =C2=A7 929P(a), Congress gave the SEC the power to bri=
ng securities fraud actions for monetary penalties within the agency instea=
d of in an Article III court whenever the SEC in its unfettered discretion =
decides to do so. Thus, it gave the SEC the ability to determine which subj=
ects of its enforcement actions are entitled to Article III proceedings wit=
h a jury trial, and which are not. That was a delegation of legislative pow=
er.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This strikes me as a littl=
e weird =E2=80=94=C2=A0surely deciding what forum to sue in is an executive=
 action, not a legislative one? =E2=80=94=C2=A0and not at all necessary to =
the decision. The court could have thrown out Jarkesy=E2=80=99s fine by say=
ing that he was deprived of a jury trial, without talking about the nondele=
gation stuff.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the panel is making=
=C2=A0a broader point here. The broader point is Justice Gorsuch=E2=80=99s =
point about political accountability, an excess of lawmaking, etc.; the opi=
nion talks about those principles at length and cites Justice Gorsuch=E2=80=
=99s Gundy dissent. The point is that the nondelegation doctrine is alive a=
gain, and the Fifth Circuit is making a bet that the next time it goes befo=
re the Supreme Court it will win. The point is that the SEC=E2=80=99s=C2=A0=
<em>actual=C2=A0</em>legislative actions =E2=80=94=C2=A0writing rules about=
 stock buybacks or swaps disclosure or climate change =E2=80=94=C2=A0are no=
w in danger. It used to be accepted as a routine matter that the SEC could =
make rules under a very broad grant of power from Congress to regulate secu=
rities markets in the public interest.[8] I am not sure=C2=A0that is true a=
nymore.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This may not be a particularly big =
deal. Two judges on one panel of one appeals court found that one small par=
t of what the SEC does is an unconstitutional delegation of power. It is po=
ssible that this decision is fairly narrow: Congress did=C2=A0delegate=C2=
=A0<em>this=C2=A0</em>decision =E2=80=94=C2=A0about whether to bring cases =
in federal courts or its own forums =E2=80=94=C2=A0to the SEC, fairly recen=
tly,=C2=A0without=C2=A0<em>any </em>guidance at all, which is unusual. Perh=
aps the =E2=80=9Cintelligible principle=E2=80=9D standard allows the SEC to=
 do all of its=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>rulemaking (because Congress has mo=
stly given it some broad guidance about protecting investors in the public =
interest, and because SEC rules do help to fill in a fairly detailed statut=
ory system), but not to make this particular decision. Still.=C2=A0I think =
the Fifth Circuit went out of its way to find a nondelegation problem becau=
se the Supreme Court has changed and now there will be a lot more courts fi=
nding a lot more nondelegation problems. I think this might be a sign of wh=
ere things are going.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One immediate upshot =
of this is that some of the SEC=E2=80=99s recently proposed rules =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0on swaps disclosure, on climate, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0are hotly contro=
versial, and there have been unusually aggressive comments from industry pa=
rticipants to the effect of =E2=80=9Cif you implement these rules, we will =
sue, and we will win.=E2=80=9D When people say this, what they mean is gene=
rally that they will go to court saying that the SEC=E2=80=99s rulemaking p=
rocess was not good enough.=C2=A0Under <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/27769856.275619/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L3=
dleC9hZG1pbmlzdHJhdGl2ZV9wcm9jZWR1cmVfYWN0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2005a6c=
6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">the rules for rulemaking</a>, agencies like the SEC need to co=
nsider costs and benefits, solicit and consider public comments and give a =
rational explanation for their rules. If you don=E2=80=99t like a rule,=C2=
=A0you can sue, arguing that the SEC=E2=80=99s process was arbitrary and ca=
pricious,=C2=A0and=C2=A0people sometimes win these lawsuits. And certainly =
people were gearing up to bring those sorts of cases against the climate an=
d swaps rules.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But now you can throw in at =
the end of your brief: =E2=80=9CAlso it is unconstitutional for the SEC to =
make any rules at all about this stuff.=E2=80=9D If =E2=80=9Cthis stuff=E2=
=80=9D is climate change, you=E2=80=99ll =E2=80=A6 probably win? (Not legal=
 advice!) If =E2=80=9Cthis stuff=E2=80=9D is swaps=C2=A0disclosure =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0which does seem closer to the core of the SEC=E2=80=99s job?=C2=A0=
=E2=80=94=C2=A0you=E2=80=99ve also got a=C2=A0shot. Because now there is a =
live possibility that federal courts might say it is unconstitutional for t=
he SEC to make any rules about anything.=C2=A0</p><table class=3D"liveinten=
