om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Wells Fargo! Come on!</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Wells Fargo &amp; Co. is a big bank. A=
s a bank, it likes making money. As a general rule, banks make more money a=
s (1) they get more customers and (2) those customers open more accounts: A=
 customer with a mortgage and a credit card and online checking is generall=
y worth more than a customer with only a checking account. So Wells Fargo i=
ncentivized=C2=A0its retail-level bankers to sell more products and open mo=
re accounts. If you sold a lot of products each day, you were rewarded; if =
you did not, you were fired.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Due to difficu=
lty of attribution and measurement and motivation, Wells Fargo did=C2=A0<em=
>not </em>mainly=C2=A0reward those employees for, like, the actual lifetime=
 monetary value to Wells Fargo of the accounts that they opened. It just re=
warded them for volume of accounts opened. Adding online banking to a check=
ing account was a =E2=80=9Cproduct=E2=80=9D that counted toward your quota =
of X products per day,=C2=A0same as adding a mortgage; a checking account w=
ith $1 in it that closed in a week counted as much as a credit card that ca=
rried a $20,000 balance for years. Really just a rough cut at measurement.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Knowing that, you can figure out what happe=
ned next. Wells Fargo bankers, struggling to meet quotas, opened a lot of l=
ow-value accounts. People who signed up for checking accounts got signed up=
 for online access whether or not they wanted it; they got pushed to open c=
redit cards too. And bankers often=C2=A0went a step further and signed cust=
omers up for accounts=C2=A0<em>without their permission</em>. Occasionally =
this helped Wells Fargo and harmed the customers: They had to pay fees on a=
ccounts that they didn=E2=80=99t want or know about, and Wells Fargo collec=
ted the fees. Sometimes this harmed the customers without helping Wells Far=
go: Their credit got worse due to new debt accounts, but the accounts were =
never used and Wells Fargo never made any money. Often=C2=A0nothing happene=
d to anyone =E2=80=94=C2=A0the customers had $0-balance accounts that were =
quickly closed with no money changing hands, or free =E2=80=9Cproducts=E2=
=80=9D like online banking access that they never knew about or used =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0but the bankers got to meet their quotas.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">The point is just that Wells Fargo had a crude measure (=E2=80=9Cpr=
oducts sold=E2=80=9D) that was meant to approximate=C2=A0an important thing=
 (something like =E2=80=9Cvalue extracted out of each customer=E2=80=9D), a=
nd its overstressed retail bankers cynically optimized the crude measure ra=
ther than the important thing. And then <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/27769856.275619/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTYtMDktMDkvd2VsbHMtZmFyZ28tb3BlbmVkLWEtY291cGxlLW1p=
bGxpb24tZmFrZS1hY2NvdW50cz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTE5MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXV=
tPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA1MTkmdXRtX2NhbXBhaW=
duPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc510ba73" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Wells Fargo g=
ot in huge trouble</a> and was fined a lot of money and it was, like,=C2=A0=
<em>the=C2=A0</em>major US banking scandal of the mid-to-late-2010s?</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a crazy story from <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27769856.275619/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1l=
cy5jb20vMjAyMi8wNS8xOS9idXNpbmVzcy93ZWxscy1mYXJnby1mYWtlLWludGVydmlld3MuaHR=
